  "12-15": (
    caption: [Regulation of gene expression by insulin through a MAP kinase cascade. The insulin receptor (INSR) consists of two (cid:3) subunits on the outer face of the plasma membrane and two (cid:2) subunits that traverse the membrane and protrude from the cytosolic face. Binding of insulin to the (cid:3) subunits triggers a conformational change that allows the autophosphorylation of Tyr residues in the carboxyl-terminal domain of the (cid:2) subunits. further activates the Tyr Autophosphorylation kinase domain, which then catalyzes phosphoryla- tion of other target proteins. The signaling pathway by which insulin regulates the expression of specific genes consists of a cascade of protein kinases, each of which activates the next. INSR is a Tyr-specific kinase; the other kinases (all shown in blue) phosphorylate Ser or Thr residues. MEK is a dual- specificity kinase, which phosphorylates both a Thr and a Tyr residue in ERK (extracellular regulated kinase); MEK is mitogen-activated, ERK-activating kinase; SRF is serum response factor. 6],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
