  "12-26": (
    caption: [Role of voltage-gated and ligand-gated ion channels in neural transmission. Initially, the plasma membrane of the presynaptic neuron is polarized (inside negative) through the action of the electro- genic Na(cid:2)K(cid:2) ATPase, which pumps out 3 Na(cid:2) for every 2 K(cid:2) pumped in (see Fig. 12–25). 1 A stimulus to this neuron (not shown) causes an action potential to move along the axon (blue arrow), away from the cell body. The opening of a voltage-gated Na(cid:2) channel allows Na(cid:2) entry, and the resulting local depolarization causes the adjacent Na(cid:2) channel to open, and so on. The directionality of movement of the action poten- tial is ensured by the brief refractory period that follows the opening of each voltage-gated Na(cid:2) channel. 2 A split second after the action potential passes a point in the axon, voltage-operated K(cid:2) channels open, allowing K(cid:2) exit that brings about repolarization of the membrane (red arrow), to make it ready for the next action potential. (For clarity, Na(cid:2) channels and K(cid:2) channels are drawn on opposite sides of the axon; both types of channels are uniformly distributed in the axonal membrane.) 3 When the wave of depolarization reaches the axon tip, voltage-gated Ca2(cid:2) channels open, allowing Ca2(cid:2) entry. 4 The resulting increase in internal \[Ca2(cid:2)\] triggers exocytic release of the neurotransmitter acetyl- choline into the synaptic cleft. 5 Acetylcholine binds to a receptor on the postsynaptic neuron (or myocyte), causing its ligand-gated ion channel to open. 6 Extracellular Na(cid:2) and Ca2(cid:2) enter through this chan- nel, depolarizing the postsynaptic cell. The electrical signal has thus passed to the cell body of the postsynaptic neuron (or myocyte) and will move along its axon to a third neuron (or a myocyte) by this same sequence of events.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "12-27": (
    caption: [Voltage-gated Na1 channels of neurons. Sodium chan- nels of different tissues and organisms have a variety of subunits, but only the principal subunit ((cid:2)) is essential. (a) The (cid:2) subunit is a large protein with four homologous domains (I to IV, shown spread out here to illustrate the parts), each containing six transmembrane helices (1 to 6). Helix 4 in each domain (blue) is the voltage sensor; helix 6 (orange) is thought to be the activation gate. The segments between helices 5 and 6, the pore region (red), form the selectivity filter, and the segment connecting domains III and IV (green) is the inactivation gate. (b) (PDB ID 3RW0) Structure of a voltage-gated Na(cid:3) channel (from the bacterium Arcobacter butzleri, but probably similar to chan- nels of vertebrate neurons), with a funnel-shaped opening on the extracellular side, an ion selectivity filter, a central aqueous cavity, and the activation domain on the cytoplasmic side. (c) A schematic view of the Na(cid:3) channel. The four domains are wrapped about a central transmembrane channel lined with polar amino acid residues. The four pore regions (red) come together near the extracellular surface to form the selectivity filter, which is conserved in all Na(cid:3) channels. The filter gives the channel its ability to discriminate between Na(cid:3) and other ions of similar size. The inactivation gate (green) closes (dotted lines) soon after the activation gate opens. (d) The voltage-sensing mechanism involves movement of helix 4 (blue) perpendicular to the plane of the membrane in response to a change in transmembrane potential. As shown at the top, the strong positive charge on helix 4 allows it to be pulled inward in response to the inside-negative mem- brane potential (Vm). Depolarization lessens this pull, and helix 4 relaxes by moving outward (bottom). This movement is communicated to the activation gate (orange), inducing conformational changes that open the channel.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
